  "summary": "Simonetta, a medium, expresses deep fear and exhaustion to Raul (also referred to as Laurie or Luca) while sitting on a couch. She describes a persistent feeling that something terrible will happen to her and speaks of the terrifying \"darkness of nothingness\" she experiences during her work. Raul attempts to comfort her, attributing her distress to the pressures of being a medium and suggesting she needs rest. He presents her with letters from Professor Loche and Dr. Gurney, who both request her services, but Simonetta insists she will never summon spirits again due to a sense of great danger. Raul promises her that she will never have to summon spirits again, though he notes that her work has been a noble contribution to science.\n\nSimonetta expresses particular dread regarding an upcoming séance with Madame Ix (also referred to as Madame Exeche), a woman who has lost her only child. Simonetta finds the woman odd and intimidating, noting her tall, dark appearance and large, man-like hands. Raul reproaches Simonetta for her lack of sympathy toward a grieving mother, defending the success of previous séances, such as the one involving the spirit of \"Little Emily.\" Simonetta remains anxious, noting her physical exhaustion and her fear that her work is a \"deal with the devil.\" As she waits for the late Madame Ix, Simonetta's nervousness causes her to break a porcelain bottle. Despite her desire to cancel, Raul reminds her of the importance of the séance, emphasizing that the client is a mother seeking to see her child one last time.",
